"{\"uid\": \"skynews.com.au-australia-news-sport-nick-kyrgios-reveals-he-is-contemplating-retiring-from-professional-tennis-and-rules-himself-out-of-2024-paris-olympics-news-story-3be79d50a77d6551b506c7049de1bdc9\", \"text\": \"Tennis star Nick Kyrgios has conceded he may never return to the court again and has already ruled himself out of representing Australia in a few months time at the Olympic Games in France.  Australian tennis player Nick Kyrgios has revealed he is considering retirement from the sport he loves due to injuries, suggesting his body \\\"may never be the same again\\\".  The 28-year-old has been forced onto the sidelines for the majority of the 2023 season where he played only one game, before tearing a ligament in his right wrist.  A few months earlier, Kyrgios underwent surgery to his knee where a parameniscal cyst - caused by a small tear in his lateral meniscus - had to be drained out.  Want more news? Stream Sky News Australia's live channel here.  The issues meant the fiery player could not compete at the 2024 Australian Open for a consecutive second year as he was not fully recovered in time.  In a Sydney Morning Herald column on Wednesday, Kyrgios said he does not know when he will return to the court, but hopes to be back for Wimbledon or the US Open.  However, the former world No.13 conceded there was no guarantee.  \\\"My body may never be the same again and injuries can take you down a different path than you imagined,\\\" he wrote, later adding he could be \\\"one of the best in the world\\\" and win major tournaments \\\"if my body lets me\\\".  He also ruled himself out of the Paris Olympics in July due to \\\"unfair and unjust\\\" treatment by former chef de mission Kitty Chiller ahead of the 2016 Rio event.  \\\"One thing I will guarantee, though, is that if I am fit and ready to play, I will not be making myself available for the Olympics,\\\" he penned.  Kyrgios revealed in the column he had spoken with his agent Stuart Duguid about his future a couple of days ago and agreed his time in tennis may be over.  The 28-year-old said he has reached a \\\"crossroads in his career\\\" and was becoming excited about what his life would look like outside of professional sport.  \\\"I could travel the world making really good money commentating on the sport, doing things like I am now with my talk show interviewing guys like Gordon Ramsay and Mike Tyson,\\\" he continued in his SMH column.  \\\"That's a life people wish they had. Even the players on the circuit would love to be doing what I am doing now, but they have a different way of thinking.\\\"  The Australian athlete suggested he had more of a global reach compared to his competitors and that his world had never revolved solely around tennis.  \\\"We miss Nick! Show him some love!\\\" \\u00f0\\u0178'\\u2122Novak Djokovic was interviewed on-court by his good friend Nick Kyrgios after reaching the Australian Open semi-finals \\u00f0\\u0178\\u00a4\\u009d\\u00f0\\u0178\\u017d\\u00a4#AusOpenpic.twitter.com/oqZNez39ji  After disappointingly ruling himself out of his home Grand Slam, US sports broadcaster ESPN recruited Kyrgios as a guest commentator for a series of matches in Melbourne.  He has been using his expertise in the game to bring insightful knowledge into what players may think and the technical plays to a large American audience.  World No.1 and 10-time Australian Open champion Novak Djokovic spotted Kyrgios in the commentating box and blew him a kiss during his quarter-final win on Tuesday.  Kyrgios later interviewed him on Rod Laver Arena.  It has been said he is impressing executives, with senior vice president for production at ESPN Mark Gross open to having the Aussie commentate at more tennis events.  Late last year, he joined subscription-based website OnlyFans to \\\"create, direct and own content\\\" and to show a more \\\"intimate side\\\" to his life.  If Kyrgios does decide to retire from tennis, he will be the second Australian to do so after three-time Grand Slam champion Ash Barty quit in March 2022.  To join the conversation, pleaselog in.Do not have an account?Register  Join the conversation, you are commenting asLogout  Our Apps\"}"